      "title": "Apr 3-19, 2026",
      "writeup": "Explores the intersection of emerging technology, societal control, and cultural preservation. A significant portion of the links focuses on the governance and surveillance implications of AI, ranging from Stanford HAI’s 2026 Index and China’s interim AI measures to the ethics of Sam Altman’s leadership and biometric verification via Worldcoin. These technical entries, alongside tools like GitHub’s Career-Ops and Netflix’s Void Model, highlight a shift toward automated systems that increasingly manage human labor and digital infrastructure.\n\nIn contrast, the collection balances these high-tech developments with artistic legacy and social critique. It references the death of hip-hop pioneer Afrika Bambaataa and the preservation of visual arts through the Aadam Jacobs and William Eggleston collections. Interspersed with these are warnings regarding the erosion of privacy through \"mass surveillance infrastructure\" and the potential for AI-driven societal conflict. Collectively, the content reflects a tension between the rapid scaling of \"personal superintelligence\" and the preservation of historical, physical, and creative autonomy."
    },
